text: I love a lot of things about this, but they did change certain things from the book starting with black betty, but I don't mind the change/s if it/they served a purpose. I love how they kept in the detail of Chubs holding Liam's legs so he doesn't fall out or how Zu silently pointed and then the bullet hit the screen. However, this trailer doesn't show Ruby like the badass, sarcastic girl she was in the books and it shows a lot of red action. Don't get me wrong. This trailer and cast is everything I could hope for, but personally I'm still waiting for the scene where Ruby slaps Liam after the chase or something that shows the book more(like an adventure road trip with the white noise interfering and then how the characters get closer and how Ruby is insecure about her Orange powers and then growing stronger e.t.c). These are just my personal opinions so feel free to disagree, but I still have high hopes for this movie and nothing can be perfect. Also this may remind certain people of the x-men series, but I assure you that this is an original story with a different plot and storyline and the only thing remotely similar between the two is that it's about kid's that have power.    OKAY I JUST NOTICED THAT RIGHT AFTER THE START AROUND 0:08 CHUBS AND RUBY ARE TOGETHER AND ITS PROBABLY WHEN THEY FIGURE OUT WHAT 'EDO' MEANS AND THEN THE WAY HOW RUBY'S EYE'S TURN ORANGE AND LIAMS BLUE!!! I GOT FAITH IN THIS PEOPLE!

I get that we're in the generation of young people and start-up million pound corporations but its too obvious that movies like this are just reinforcing the idea that by sheer chance and extreme coincidence can young people be more influential than their elders. It also coincides with the story of people being born into specific families and/ or wealth, which propogates the diminishing influence hard work has on greatness. So no, I will not be supporting this movie by watching it and I hope others wont too. We live in a time in which all of us need to work hard and take responsibility for our own lives.

text: OH MY GOD!!!! I HAVE BEEN WAITING FOR THIS MOVIE TO COME OUT FOR TWO YEARS NOW!! I AM FREAKING OUT NOW! OH MY GOD, OH MY GOD, OH MY GOD, OH MY GOD, OH MY- *takes in deep breath to calm down* Yeah. I really have been waiting for two years for this to come out, and although, it does look good and interesting, I am still not very fond of the actors chosen to play the parts of Ruby, Liam, Chubs, and Zu. I am sure they can play the part pretty well, but I feel as if they may not capture their full personalities, and then there is the fact that they don't look so much like their book characters, especially Ruby. Also, Zu should have very short hair, Chubs should have shorter hair and his glasses don't seem to look like his silver wired frame glasses in the book, Liam doesn't have his southern accent and his hair isn't as blonde, then there is Ruby who us obviously very different.  One more thing, what's up with the glowing eyes? Is that to show that she is using her ability to the audience or is that supposed to be an actual thing that others can see within the world?

text: For those who are confused. The children in this movie are under five classification and kids with these abilities are put in a certain section which has a unique color of it's own. *Red* Is for those who can control fire. *Yellow*  is for those who can control electricity. *Blue*  is for those can  move things with their minds *Green*  is for those who are highly intelligent. In this Movie our dear Ruby (the female lead) will disguise herself as being Green so she can hide who she truly is. Which takes us to our final and most powerful ability. *Orange*  The power to control emotions, thoughts, memories. The power to control people's mind. text: From what I understand, people think this looks generic and then automatically assume itâ€™ll be bad.  But why?  Sure, superpowers arenâ€™t the most original or exciting thing anymore and it appears to play out some classic YA tropes, but thatâ€™s not a bad thing.  Their target is young adults so making the protagonists their age only makes sense, so thatâ€™s why theyâ€™re all kids and teens.  If that bothers you then youâ€™re not their target audience and that wonâ€™t affect them one way or another.  Furthermore, please understand that tropes are reoccurring ideas in entertainment because they became popular.  Only when they are overused and become a tool rather than an idea does it become a cliche, so having precedent tropes does not automatically make it bad.  Now as someone who only found out this is based on a book series, Iâ€™m still highly intrigued.  I enjoy super powered plots (especially when that doesnâ€™t automatically translate into being a superhero) and will probably watch this.  I know itâ€™s a lot to ask, but please stop saying something will be garbage just because it follows a YA format and has powers (and that doesnâ€™t make it an X-Men rip-off either).

text: Siiiiigh, people complaining about "forced diversity". Like it's crazy that any non-white person would want to see themselves reflected on the big screen. This nation is predominantly white so almost all forms of media is dominated by white characters. That's all well and good, because, duh, but I don't see the problem with diversifying casts when a written format is translated for our screens. More people are going to buy a movie ticket or turn on their television than are going to buy a book. And giving us characters that are representative of like, 40% of the nation is a great idea. You couldn't do something like that 10 years ago and get away with it (people still complain, but that's the minority, thankfilly)

text: Ok for the ppl who r annoyed at ruby not being what u guys imagined:   Just let it go. The only time i might get a little pissy is if it was a historically accurate movie and make a poc white. Not every poc gets upset when they are being played by a white person. Other than that, it's nice to have an asian girl as one of the main leads. That doesn't happen often. Ruby and Chubs (forgive me I haven't read the book)  get a main lead to have a positive representation. Not as a ratchet ghetto hood person. I get what you people are saying about "it's not what it was in the book", however why should it matter. It isn't propaganda or sjw. It is what it is. If movie creators want to make this movie in particular and change the characters up a bit...that's fine. As long as they can act, i'm fine by it. Even tho u guys (not all but some) always complain "why is it always about race?!" Try and be stared at most of the time uncomfortably or be automatically stereotyped sometimes for other people to have a bad opinion about you. Try being arrested for no other reason yet you are going on about ur day, but you are Asian, Black, Hispanic, Native American etcetera. Representation is important because race is all around us. Some people won't believe how often how much sh*t poc put up with to anybody who is racist. I said anybody because some white ppl aren't always the cause of racism. Anyone can.

text: I.. have problems with this. I'm very happy that a movie adaptation is happening, but a lot is untrue.  -Liam should have a southern accent. and I'm sure we all pictured him more blonde, as he was described in the books  -zu is supposed to have close to no hair. I think they could've put the actress in a wig to create the illusion of it atleast  -no reds were part of the first book. they were only talked about.  -ruby. touchy subject. I think it's cool that more black representation is in Hollywood. it's a great step forward for how casting goes. but, her hair had been discribed as straight/tangled and her eyes green. I seriously doubt any author would describe curly-kinky hair as "tangled". and since she was taken as a child I will assume that wigs were not a part of life, nor were they mentioned. I say all this about her hair because I have yet to meet or know of a black person born with straight hair. it's just traits of their race, like how asian people will usually have dark eyes/hair. I hope I don't come off as "anti-black" or anything. my whole problem about this is that the director took it to herself to decide Ruby's race which is contradicting to what the books told us. sidenote: her name. Ruby Elizabeth Daly. Daly is of  Irish origins. thought I'd mention this.  -the van! justice should be delivered for Black Betty. she is a "mom van"!  -that scene with an amphitheater/arena ish look. never mentioned in the first book at all. also don't know why all those kids had their color painted on themselves. where did they come from? don't know. it's untrue.  -I get the suspicion that the plot has been reformed in some places and can't say I'm liking that too much

text: so I guess people are upset that Ruby isn't white, and while it isn't how I pictured her when I read the book, I literally did just finish a reread of it yesterday and as far as I can tell, it NEVER described her as being white.  It never described her race at all - It did with Zu and Chubs, but not Ruby.  The most descriptors the book ever gave about her were that she had long dark curly hair, an average build, shorter than the boys in the group, and possibly something about her eyes, but I can't remember that one.  So while its not what you may have imagined, its not technically an issue because it was never described. text: *This is just my opinion ,if someone actually reads this thanks (: and sorry for the long comment.* Some people in the comments say that this was a copy of Hunger games,and they have a point because all of the books /movies that are based of them like The Maze Runner ,this and many more are all about stories that happen in a dystopic society,meaning the opposite of an utopic society,where everything is perfect,so basically the worst case scenario.   In my opinion the plots are interesting and the acting is mediocre(not always)  ,but at one point they simply become predictable and dull since all of the books and movies are not identical BUT all have the same structure.(Some of the books are really good as well as some movies). I personally belive that filmmakers are very aware of all this,but instead of trying to approach a different concept beacuse it risks to be a commercial failure ,they will probably keep making these kind of movies for some time since the majority of the public enjoys them . I think this movie was alright ,but not amazing.  *Thanks again to anyone that took the time to read this and also if you a have a different opinion feel free to reply to my comment ,but please do it in an apropriate way I do not want to argue with anyone (:*

The little girl!  ... and at every turn we see our lovely boring cast holding her back.  ...another thing that burned me was this "Girl Power" CRAP!   Just one scene prior she (Ruby) couldn't even get her thoughts together and didn't even know how to use her random ability.  NO TRAINING WHATSOEVER! (SPOILER) Final showdown, she's controlling an army?! GTFOH!!!  Reminds me of the reviews i read about "The Last Jedi" nonsense...STILL REFUSE TO WATCH THAT ONE!!!  No issues with Ladies kicking butt... in fact, I think its HOT... but EARN YOUR KEEP!  This movie gets a 3/10 from me. It has some awesome potential, but suffered because of poor/dull storytelling and terrible character development.

text: When your 3rd last and last scenes of your movie are in your trailer, you have a bad trailer  When the climactic attack - not just climactic battle, the climactic attack - is in your trailer, you have a bad trailer  In fact, two entire fight sequences have their climactic attack in this trailer  Overall, the trailer clearly ignored the suspense of the movie and instead went for the raw power moments which meant all the good stuff was spoiled and you didn't think it was anything other than a dumb action flick...  I'm thinking of possible trailer designs.  I'm thinking start with the escape moment, focus on her mind controlling the guard and Cate's "Oh my God", and then set the scene of how it all started (girl at start dying, no kids, fear of survivors, concentration camps, violence at the camps) then build up all the threats that you face in the world after escaping and play up how everyone wants something and the distrust element.  Don't show anything from them reaching ED0 onwards (maybe a shot of reds throwing fireballs for the list of threats) - just build up to it and you could possibly hint with the "I can show you how to control your powers" towards the end.

I think that at all times the movie maintains a good level, it will keep you basnate engaged with the story and eager to know how the chaos will end.  The fact that the protagonist passes different things (such as celebrating a victory, feeling joy with adrenaline, or a large void due to his actions), makes me as a spectator get me much more into the movie, and that is affected in each scene. Which seems a pretty necessary detail!  That's why I think it's a good movie, and a good start for a great story.  . text: 20th Century Fox must cull negative comments, because I've heard more bad about this movie than good!  Yet, not one single negative comment on a movie that was Down Voted 7.7k times?   Yeah right!  Anyway, the movie leaves more questions unanswered than it answers, the acting is mediocre at best, and the story line is weak. The producers offset the weak story line by flipping scenes, literally every 2 minutes.  I didn't count one single scene in the movie that was over 2 minutes long.  One question?  What do the adults in the movie assume will happen to all of the 'kids' when the adults can no longer contain them due to their old age?  Nothing about this movie makes sense, and it was a total waste of time.  I mean, could they have drilled the "You're special and Adults are Bad" any more than they did in this movie?  Seriously.  History will, hopefully, forget this filth.

text: WORST ENDING EVER! They should've at least given it a good closing ending and not leave it open ended. They probably thought it was going to be a hit movie so they left the ending for a second movie. But, the sequel WILL NEVER happen. They barely even made their money back from the box office. This movie reminded me of The Hunger Games. The only difference is that The Hunger Games actually had a closing ending to each movie. And once they secured the budget for all the sequels they were able to make an ending like this movie did. This movie went ahead of themselves and ended the movie with the start of a revolution which sadly we will never get to see. All movies should have a Beginning, Middle, and END! This movie only had a Beginning and Middle, NO END. Movies are only allowed to have these types of endings when they have a budget secured for all the sequels. They shouldn't do it for the first movie since it doesn't always work out at the box office.
